	abstract = {This paper discusses the reconstruction of uvular and labio-uvular stops in Old Chinese, originally proposed by Pan Wuyun. The following two improvements are proposed: (I) the Old Chinese non labialized voiced uvular stop evolved to Middle Chinese y- (llfilw) rather than hj- (Jlfir.s) in Pan's theory (which implies that Middle Chinese y- has two sources in Old Chinese: *I- and *o-); (2) uvulars and labio-uvulars evolve to MC velars when preceded by a minor syllable. This explains why velars and uvulars frequently alternate in phonetic series. The article also explores the evolution of (labio)uvulars in the context of different prefixes.},
